Note:
CSS to HIR Translator

Translates CSS AST to Runa HIR.

Translation Mapping:
- CSS_STYLESHEET → Dictionary {type: "stylesheet", rules: [...]}
- CSS_RULE → Dictionary {type: "rule", selectors: [...], declarations: [...]}
- CSS_AT_RULE → Dictionary {type: "at-rule", name: "...", rules: [...]}
- CSS_SELECTOR → String
- CSS_DECLARATION → Dictionary {property: "...", value: "..."}
- CSS_VALUE → String or nested structure
- CSS_FUNCTION → Dictionary {type: "function", name: "...", args: [...]}
- CSS_COMMENT → Dictionary {type: "comment", value: "..."}
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/css/css_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry: parses CSS source via the CSS parser, then translates the
resulting AST to the HIR Dict shape. Two-stage so callers can swap in a
different AST source (e.g. an editor's incremental parse) by calling
translate_node directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls Parser.parse_css on the source string; on parse failure (0 return)
propagates 0. Otherwise walks the AST root via translate_node. The options
argument is reserved for future use (target profile, vendor-prefix policy)
and is currently passed unused.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
source is untrusted CSS text. Parser handles malformed input by returning 0;
this routine therefore never dereferences a malformed AST.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_css_to_hir" takes source as Integer, options as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast be proc parse_css from Parser with source

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_node from ast

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-table dispatcher keyed on node_type (200..207 are the CSS AST node
type constants emitted by css_parser). Each type has a dedicated
translator; null node and unknown type both return 0 so the caller can
treat 0 as "no HIR was produced".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node_type at offset 0. Branches: 200 stylesheet, 201 rule, 202 at-rule,
203 selector, 204 declaration, 205 value, 206 function, 207 comment.
Anything outside the range falls through to Return 0 (silent skip - the
walk continues).
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_node" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0

    If node_type is equal to 200:
        Return proc translate_stylesheet from node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to 201:
        Return proc translate_rule from node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to 202:
        Return proc translate_at_rule from node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to 203:
        Return proc translate_selector from node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to 204:
        Return proc translate_declaration from node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to 205:
        Return proc translate_value from node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to 206:
        Return proc translate_function from node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to 207:
        Return proc translate_comment from node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A CSS stylesheet is the top-level container of rules and at-rules. HIR
captures it as {type:"stylesheet", rules:[...]} so consumers can iterate
rules uniformly regardless of nesting depth.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates an output Dict with type="stylesheet". Reads child_count at
offset 32 and children pointer-array at offset 24, then translates each
child through translate_node. Non-null translations are pushed onto a
"rules" List which is attached to the Dict before return.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_stylesheet" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dict be proc create_dictionary

    Let type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string from StringCore with "stylesheet"
    proc dict_set with dict, type_key, type_value

    Let rules_list be proc create_list

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24

    Let index be 0
    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, index multiplied by 8
        Let child_hir be proc translate_node from child

        If child_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc list_append with rules_list, child_hir
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Let rules_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "rules"
    proc dict_set with dict, rules_key, rules_list

    Return dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
A CSS rule is "selectors { declarations }". HIR splits the rule's children
into two parallel lists - selectors (203) and declarations (204) - so
downstream consumers don't have to scan a heterogeneous child list to
distinguish a selector from a property:value pair.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates Dict with type="rule" and two empty Lists (selectors,
declarations). Walks children: child_type 203 -> translate_selector ->
selectors list; child_type 204 -> translate_declaration -> declarations
list; other child types are ignored to keep the rule shape clean.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_rule" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dict be proc create_dictionary

    Let type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string from StringCore with "rule"
    proc dict_set with dict, type_key, type_value

    Let selectors_list be proc create_list
    Let declarations_list be proc create_list

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24

    Let index be 0
    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, index multiplied by 8
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

        If child_type is equal to 203:
            Let selector_hir be proc translate_selector from child
            If selector_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc list_append with selectors_list, selector_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to 204:
            Let decl_hir be proc translate_declaration from child
            If decl_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc list_append with declarations_list, decl_hir
            End If
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Let selectors_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "selectors"
    proc dict_set with dict, selectors_key, selectors_list

    Let declarations_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "declarations"
    proc dict_set with dict, declarations_key, declarations_list

    Return dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
At-rules (@media, @import, @keyframes, @font-face, @supports, ...) have a
name and an optional nested block. HIR captures them as
{type:"at-rule", name, rules:[...]} preserving the nested rule list for
block-form at-rules while a name-only form (@import) yields an empty rules
list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates Dict with type="at-rule"; reads the at-rule name from offset 8
of the AST node and stores it under "name". Walks children identically to
translate_stylesheet (every child dispatched through translate_node) and
attaches them under "rules".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_at_rule" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dict be proc create_dictionary

    Let type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string from StringCore with "at-rule"
    proc dict_set with dict, type_key, type_value

    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let name_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "name"
    proc dict_set with dict, name_key, name

    Let rules_list be proc create_list

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24

    Let index be 0
    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, index multiplied by 8
        Let child_hir be proc translate_node from child

        If child_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc list_append with rules_list, child_hir
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Let rules_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "rules"
    proc dict_set with dict, rules_key, rules_list

    Return dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
Selectors are emitted by the parser already as a single flattened value
string ("h1.title, .nav > li.active::hover") so the translator simply
unwraps the value field and returns it directly. No Dict shell is needed
because the rule's "selectors" array stores each selector as a bare string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the selector text from offset 16 (value slot) and returns it
verbatim. Borrowed StringCore pointer; the rule Dict assumes ownership when
the result is appended to its selectors list.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_selector" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
A declaration is "property: value" inside a rule block. HIR captures it as
{property, value} so consumers can iterate properties without indexing into
a heterogeneous child list. Only the FIRST value child is consumed because
a single declaration in CSS holds exactly one property:value pair (compound
values like "10px solid red" are already concatenated into the value
slot by the parser).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates Dict with property field copied from node offset 8. If the
declaration has at least one child (value node), reads its value-string
from offset 16 of the child and attaches it under "value". A bare-property
declaration (no value child) yields a Dict with only the property key,
which the back-end treats as malformed.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_declaration" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dict be proc create_dictionary

    Let property be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let property_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "property"
    proc dict_set with dict, property_key, property

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let value_node be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value_node, 16

        Let value_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "value"
        proc dict_set with dict, value_key, value
    End If

    Return dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
Value nodes are leaf nodes that carry the literal value text from the
parser. HIR returns the bare value string just like translate_selector
because the declaration Dict consumes it directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the value text at offset 16 and returns it. Borrowed StringCore
pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_value" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS functions (rgb(), calc(), url(), var()) appear inside declaration
values. They're emitted as {type:"function", name} so consumers can
distinguish them from bare values without re-parsing the value text. The
argument list is not unpacked at this layer; tools that need the
arguments parse them on demand from the original value string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates Dict with type="function" and name copied from the AST node's
name slot at offset 8. The function's argument expression remains in the
parent declaration's value text.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_function" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dict be proc create_dictionary

    Let type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string from StringCore with "function"
    proc dict_set with dict, type_key, type_value

    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let name_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "name"
    proc dict_set with dict, name_key, name

    Return dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS comments survive into HIR so source-map and round-trip printing remain
faithful. Captured as {type:"comment", value} with value being the raw
comment text excluding the /* */ delimiters.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates Dict with type="comment"; copies the comment text from offset 16
of the AST node into the "value" key. Used by formatters and IDEs to
preserve developer notes.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_comment" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dict be proc create_dictionary

    Let type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string from StringCore with "comment"
    proc dict_set with dict, type_key, type_value

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    Let value_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "value"
    proc dict_set with dict, value_key, value

    Return dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS-local Dict so the translator stays self-contained (the CSS translator
intentionally avoids the heavy collections module to keep CSS support
dependency-light). Fixed initial capacity of 10 since typical CSS Dicts
in HIR hold 2-6 entries (type, name, rules, selectors, declarations, value).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte header (size, capacity, keys ptr, values ptr) and two
80-byte parallel arrays (10 i64 slots each) for keys and values. The keys
and values pointers are written into the header at offsets 16/24. On OOM
(allocate returns 0) propagates 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_dictionary" returns Integer:
    Let dict_size be 32
    Let dict be proc allocate from Layout with dict_size

    If dict is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dict, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dict, 8, 10
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dict, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dict, 24, 0

    Let keys be proc allocate from Layout with 80
    Let values be proc allocate from Layout with 80

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dict, 16, keys
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dict, 24, values

    Return dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append-only Dict insert without uniqueness checks because the translator
controls every key it inserts and never overwrites. Skipping the linear
search keeps insertion O(1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current size from offset 0 and the keys/values arrays from offsets
16/24. Writes (key, value) at the size-th slot (offset size*8) in both
parallel arrays, increments size. Does not handle resize because CSS HIR
Dicts stay under the 10-entry capacity by construction; callers that need
more should switch to the general Dict module.
@End Implementation

Process called "dict_set" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dict, 0
    Let keys be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dict, 16
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dict, 24

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with keys, size multiplied by 8, key
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with values, size multiplied by 8, value

    Set size to size plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dict, 0, size

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS-local List, paired with the local Dict. Same justification: keep the
CSS translator self-contained and dependency-light. Initial capacity of 10
covers typical CSS HIR lists (rule selectors, declarations within a rule,
top-level stylesheet rules of small style files).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte header (size, capacity, items ptr) and an 80-byte items
array (10 i64 slots). The items pointer is written into the header at
offset 16. On OOM returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_list" returns Integer:
    Let list_size be 24
    Let list be proc allocate from Layout with list_size

    If list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with list, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with list, 8, 10
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with list, 16, 0

    Let items be proc allocate from Layout with 80

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with list, 16, items

    Return list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append-only insert. Symmetric with dict_set, also unchecked against the
fixed 10-slot capacity because the translator's insertion patterns stay
within it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads size from offset 0 and items pointer from offset 16. Writes item at
slot offset size*8, increments size. No resize.
@End Implementation

Process called "list_append" takes list as Integer, item as Integer returns Integer:
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with list, 0
    Let items be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with list, 16

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with items, size multiplied by 8, item

    Set size to size plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with list, 0, size

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Single-Argument Source Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public single-arg facade invoked by the translation dispatcher's
LANG_CSS arm. The underlying translate_css_to_hir already accepts
a raw source-string plus an options pointer; this wrapper forwards
to it with options=0 (default profile, no vendor-prefix override).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Direct forward to translate_css_to_hir(source_code, 0). Returns 0
on parse failure (propagated from the underlying call).
@End Implementation

Process called "css_to_hir_from_source" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc translate_css_to_hir with source_code, 0
End Process

Note: End of CSS to HIR Translator
